flowRoot.flowPara: Data arranged by age and time is often viewed as a Lexis surface by adding contours or shading to the Lexis diagram. This lets you see one layer of information at a time. Bivariate surfaces are basically unheard of for demographic data on the Lexis grid.

We propose adding a layer of symbolically encoded information to the classic Lexis surface: vector fields. Vector fields in general use segments or arrows to display variation in force and direction over a coordinate plane,

A vector field snapped on the Lexis plane could be called a Lexis field. Even higher information densities can be acheived without (we think) loss in legibility by overlapping Lexis fields with Lexis surfaces. This brings us a step closer to turning Lexis surfaces into Lexis maps.
Everyone likes maps.

flowRoot.flowPara: We have male and female fertility rates for Sweden, years 1968 to 2015.
This figure has two layers:
1) a filled contour Lexis surface of female fertility rates for Sweden.

2) a vector field showing the log ratio of female to male fertility. Upward sloping segments mean that female fertility is higher, and vice versa. The crossover age (the age where male and female rates are equal) is shown with a thick white line.

Each layer is interesting all by itself, but here we can see that the crossover age is higher than the modal age of female fertility in a regular way, and that increases in the crossover age have roughly kept pace with increases in the age of motherhood.
There are other (space greedier) ways to show as much information as this, but the overlaying is key.

Logging the ratios makes sense (here and in other visualization contexts) because 1/2 and 2 are in a sense the same distance from 1. When we translate to slopes on the field, these end up being the same slope magnitude, but either down-sloping or upsloping, respectively.
Here's a rough key to eyeball:
We have female lifetables from all HMD countries, years 1950 forward.
This figure has two layers
1) A filled contour Lexis surface of the coefficient of variation of remaining lifespan (HMD average). That is, the ratio of the standard deviation to the mean.
2) A vector field showing how the linear relationship between the standard deviation and mean vary over age and time.

Field points are encoded to indicate some characteristics of the relationship: Slopes are proportional to linear regression coefficients. Length is proportional to the spread in both variables. Darker line shades indicate stronger correlation.

In young ages more life expectancy is correlated with lower standard deviation in the death distribution, but in older ages the relationship is reversed. The crossover age has been moving up over time.

Displaying a larger variety of demographic quantities on the Lexis plane and increasing the information density on the Lexis plane using symbolic layering techniques such as fields could broaden the scope of demographic exploration and comparisons, and sharpen the instruments of demographic pattern detection
There are proposals to visualize compositional data on the Lexis surface, which is in some ways similar. See Schöley and Willekens (2017)
